    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-08T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-08T10:00:00-05:00" n="338"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d338">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War/9–844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Greek Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-08T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 8, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Greek 297. Ankara telegram 1635, September 2 to Department. The course of events
                    in Cairo does not seem to justify the Turkish criticism of British delay in
                    conducting armistice negotiations.</p>
                <p>The British brought the Bulgarian delegate to Cairo by special plane the day
                    after his arrival at Istanbul (Istanbul telegram to Department August 30, 10
                    a.m.).</p>
                <pb facs="0417" n="405" xml:id="pg_405"/>
                <p>Conversations with Moushanov began September 1, the same day that Shantz received
                    authority to act.</p>
                <p>Subsequent delay was caused by Moushanov’s reluctance to proceed with the
                    negotiations for reasons given in Embassy’s telegram Greek 278, 286 and 290<note
                        n="71" xml:id="d338fn71">Telegram Greek 290, September 5, 8 p.m., not
                        printed.</note> of September 1, 4 and 5 respectively.</p>
                <p>Repeated to London as 28, to Moscow and Ankara.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
